{{Infobox artwork | image_file = Jesus as a Manichaean Prophet, 13th century.jpg | painting_alignment = right | image_size = 270px | title = Manichaean Painting of the Buddha Jesus | other_language_1=[[Traditional Chinese characters|Chinese]] | other_title_1={{lang|zh-Hant|夷數佛幀|italic=no}} | other_language_2=[[Japanese language|Japanese]] | other_title_2={{lang|ja|キリスト聖像|italic=no}} | artist = Unknown | year = 12th to 13th centuries | type = Hanging scroll, colours and gold on silk | height_metric = 153.5 | width_metric = 58.7 | height_imperial = | width_imperial = | city = [[Kōshū, Yamanashi|Kōshū]] | museum = {{ill|Seiunji Temple|ja|棲雲寺}} }}
The '''''Manichaean Painting of the Buddha Jesus''''' ({{lang-zh|t=夷數佛幀|w=I2-shu4 fo2-chên1|p=Yí shù fó zhēn}}; {{CJKV|j=キリスト聖像<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.tenmokusan.or.jp/pdf/seiunji/20110916.pdf |title=天目山栖雲寺 宝物風入れ展：虚空蔵菩薩画像（キリスト聖像）特別公開 |website=tenmokusan.or.jp |language=ja |accessdate=28 November 2018}}</ref>|r=Kirisuto Sei-zō|l=Sacred Image of Christ}}), is a Chinese [[Southern Song dynasty]] [[silk painting|silk]] [[hanging scroll]] preserved at the {{ill|Seiunji Temple|ja|棲雲寺}} in [[Kōshū, Yamanashi]], Japan. It measures 153.5 cm in height, 58.7 cm in width, dates from the 12th to 13th centuries, and depicts a solitary [[nimbate]] figure on a dark-brown medieval Chinese silk. According to the Hungarian historian [[Zsuzsanna Gulácsi]], this painting is one of the six documented [[Chinese Manichaeism|Chinese Manichaean]] hanging scrolls from [[Zhejiang]] province from the early 12th century, which titled {{transl|zh|Yishu fo zhen}} (lit. "Silk Painting of the Buddha [Prophet] Jesus").{{refn|group=note|"{{lang|zh-Hant|夷數}}" ({{lang-zh|w=I-shu|p=Yíshù}}) is the Chinese translation of the name ''Jesus'' by the Manichaeans.}}<ref name="AMPBJ">{{cite web |url=http://www.academia.edu/27929108/_A_Manichaean_Portrait_of_the_Buddha_Jesus_Identifying_a_Twelfth-Thirteenth-century_Chinese_Painting_from_the_Collection_of_Seiun-ji_Zen_Temple._Artibus_Asiae_69_1_2009_91-145 |title=A Manichaean Portrait of the Buddha Jesus |last=Gulácsi |first=Zsuzsanna |date=2009 |website=academia.edu |access-date=28 November 2018}}</ref>
== Description == [[File:Manichaean Painting of the Buddha Jesus (detail).jpg|thumb|left|300px|Detail: Cross of Light.]] The painting depicts a monumental, solitary figure, with glittering lines of gold and various colours. The upper half is occupied by a cloaked deity seated in [[lotus position]] and hands held close to one another in front of the chest. He is holding in his left hand a red lotus pedestal on where a small gold cross (Cross of Light) is seated. In addition to the [[Halo (religious iconography)|nimbus]] around the head, there is a faint outline of a large [[mandorla]] that frames the body and reaches the upwards, where a [[Tassel|tasselled]] [[Chatra (umbrella)|canopy]] hung above the nimbus. The lower half is filled by an elaborate pedestal, which is a multilayered hexagonal stand supporting a lotus with lush sets of petals that open in five orderly rings. Each petal evokes the form of a miniature altar.
== Background == According to the ''[[Song Huiyao Jigao]]'', there were six paintings in the possession of a Chinese Manichaean church used as objects of learning and veneration:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cciv.cityu.edu.hk/publication/jiuzhou/txt/15-2-190.txt |title=摩尼教華名辨異 |last=Lin |first=Wushu |website=cciv.cityu.edu.hk |language=zh-Hant |accessdate=28 November 2018}}</ref> * Silk painting of the buddha Wonderful Water ({{lang|zh-Hant|妙水佛幀}}) * Silk painting of the buddha First Thought ({{lang|zh-Hant|先意佛幀}}) * '''Silk painting of the buddha Jesus''' ({{lang|zh-Hant|夷數佛幀}}) * Silk painting of Good and Evil ({{lang|zh-Hant|善惡幀}}) * Silk painting of the Royal Prince ({{lang|zh-Hant|太子幀}}) * Silk painting of the Four Kings of Heaven ({{lang|zh-Hant|四天王幀}})
== History == The history of this hanging scroll represents a unique case of religious metamorphosis, for it has been used by three religions. It can be divided into three episodes: before ca. 1552, the image was venerated by [[Chinese Manichaeism|Manichaeans]] from southern China. From 1552 (or 1608) to 1612, during this period of sixty years (at most), the painting functioned as a [[Kirishitan|Christian]] object in Japan. No written records, only legend at [[Seiunji Temple]], suggests that the painting belonged to an executed Christian [[daimyō]] [[Arima Harunobu]], before it ended up in the Buddhist temple. The most recent, which has lasted approximately four hundred years, when the scroll has been used as a [[Buddhism in Japan|Buddhist]] work of art in the Seiunji Temple in Japan.<ref name="AMPBJ" /> The Japanese Buddhists considered it a depiction of [[Ākāśagarbha]] ({{lang-ja|虚空蔵菩薩}}), a celestial [[bodhisattva]] worshipped in [[Vajrayana|Esoteric Buddhism]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.academia.edu/28622189/_A_Song_Dynasty_Manichaean_Painting_of_the_Buddha_Jesus_%E5%B9%85%E5%AE%8B%E4%BB%A3%E6%91%A9%E5%B0%BC%E6%95%99_%E5%A4%B7%E6%95%B0%E4%BD%9B%E5%B8%A7_Yifu_Songdai_Monijiao_Yishufozheng_._Journal_for_the_Study_of_Art_History_%E8%89%BA%E6%9C%AF%E5%8F%B2%E7%A0%94%E7%A9%B6_Yishushi_Yanjiu_2008_139-189_in_Chinese_ |title=一幅宋代摩尼敎《夷數佛幀》 |last=Gulácsi |first=Zsuzsanna |translator-last=Wang |translator-first=Yuanyuan |date=2008 |website=academia.edu |language=zh-Hant |accessdate=28 November 2018}}</ref>
== Analysis == The painting was identified earlier by the Japanese art historian {{ill|Takeo Izumi|ja|泉武夫 (美術史学者)}} as a [[Yuan dynasty]] [[Church of the East in China|Nestorian Christian]] work of art. [[Zsuzsanna Gulácsi]] notes that the highly [[Sinicization|sinicised]] character of this painting weakens this idea, "since [[Church of the East|Nestorian Christianity]] in China maintained a foreign identity and produced art with relatively small degree of integration compared to the arts of other originally foreign but later fully integrated religions, such as Buddhism and Manichaeism."<ref name="AMPBJ" />
After studying and comparing the scroll with a number of Buddhist, Nestorian Christian and Manichaean works of art, Gulácsi concluded in her article ''A Manichaean Portrait of the Buddha Jesus: Identifying a Twelfth-Thirteenth-century Chinese Painting from the Collection of Seiun-ji Zen Temple'', that the painting is a Manichaean work of art: {{Quote|text=Despite the fact that it features a figure seated on a lotus pedestal with a cross statuette in his left hand, this painting is neither a Buddhist nor a Christian work of art for three reasons: first, it can be linked with contemporaneous Chinese textual and visual sources that support its creation and used in a Manichaean context; second, it displays iconographic and compositional continuity with earlier Manichaean art; and third, it depicts a Manichaean subject (the prophet Jesus) with symbols that allude to two fundamental Manichaean teachings ([[Dualistic cosmology|Dualism]] and the Cross of Light) that are well documented throughout the history of this religion. Based on a contemporaneous inventory of paintings in the possession of a Manichaean temple in [[Wenzhou]], this hanging scroll may be titled {{transl|zh|Yishu fo zhen}} (Silk Painting of the Buddha ["Prophet"] Jesus). Its attribution and identification help us to comfirm that the Jesus subject had a long history in Manichaean devotional art, which now can be seen through two fragments from [[Xinjiang|East Central Asia]] and a third, exquisitely well preserved, from southern China.<ref name="AMPBJ" />}}
